  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Four-Character Teachings Inscribed and Presented to My Son, the Lord of Gilcheon
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Impartiality—when the heart is just, it harbors no selfish desire.
    The mind grows clear, free from craving,
    and all deeds flow from rightness itself.
    This is what we call Integrity.

    Diligence—when effort is constant, laziness finds no purchase.
    With earnest application, faults are prevented,
    and duties never fall to ruin.
    This is what we call Loyalty and Virtue.

    Generosity—when the heart is broad, harshness dissolves.
    All affairs become touched by benevolence,
    becoming the virtue of the noble man,
    and blessings flow down through generations yet unborn.

    Trustworthiness—when faith is true, falsehood cannot take hold.
    Hold fast to sincerity,
    keep steadfast your purpose,
    and never alter your path by your own hand.
  footnotes:
    - 'This work is structured as a moral primer, each quatrain beginning with a single Chinese character (公勤寬信) representing core Confucian virtues: Impartiality, Diligence, Generosity, and Trustworthiness.'
    - Gwon Geun (1352-1409) was a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar and official of the Joseon Dynasty, known for his philosophical writings and moral instruction to his descendants.
